because of that, I fall into the trap of trying to make everyone like me, everyone understand me, and work overtime to fix relationships I feel are broken.... What I’m trying now is to give a little less fucks. And if you judge me or even hate me for living my truth, oh well! 🤷

Invariably, as a kid who was starved of the validation of their peers, I occasionally go into hoarding mode, where that validation from ANYONE is a NEED, and to lose that validation—to have anyone turn their backs on me for whatever reason—feels like the end of the world...

What I learned over the years is the best way to be accepted by your peers is *first* to accept yourself. If you can rep for yourself and really not have any shame about it, that confidence is contagious. People look up to that kind of positive energy.
And yet I was so isolated. Dying to be noticed but more than anything, dying to be accepted. My mistake was assuming I had to fit the mold to be accepted, rather than be myself.

(my exp.) I spent years caring a lot of what others may have thought of me. In high school the thought of changing anything such as my hairstyle was overwhelming. I had been conditioned to associate any attention I received with bullying and therefore wanted to blend in fully.

At the end of their chapter, no one is going to say “I wish I’d been more self-conscious” but one might wish they’d given themselves some more slack to be whatever them wanted to be and lived a little more.
Life is too sweet to let your fear of other’s judgement limit what you do. (a thread)
